.TH GIT-STAGE-BATCH 1 "March 2026" "git-stage-batch @VERSION@" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
git-stage-batch \- hunk-by-hunk and line-by-line staging for git
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B git-stage-batch
[\fB\-i\fR|\fB\-\-interactive\fR]
[\fB\-\-version\fR]
[\fICOMMAND\fR [\fIARGS\fR...]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B git-stage-batch
provides a workflow for staging changes to git in a structured, reviewable way.
Unlike \fBgit add -p\fR, it maintains state across commands, allowing you to
pause and resume, and provides fine-grained line-level control.
.PP
The tool works by finding hunks in your diff, presenting them one at a time,
and letting you include (stage), skip, or discard each hunk or individual lines
within hunks. State is maintained in \fB.git/git-stage-batch/\fR so you can
stop and continue later, or run git commands between operations.
.SH WORKFLOW
A typical workflow:
.IP 1. 4
\fBgit-stage-batch start\fR - Begin reviewing changes
.IP 2.
Review the displayed hunk
.IP 3.
\fBgit-stage-batch include\fR - Stage this hunk, or
.br
\fBgit-stage-batch skip\fR - Skip for now, or
.br
\fBgit-stage-batch discard\fR - Remove from working tree
.IP 4.
Repeat until done
.IP 5.
\fBgit commit\fR - Commit staged changes
.IP 6.
\fBgit-stage-batch again\fR - Review remaining hunks for next commit
.SH COMMANDS
.SS Session Management
.TP
.BR start " [" \-U \fIN\fR ]
Find and display the first unprocessed hunk. Optionally set context lines with \fB-U\fR (default: 3).
.TP
.BR show ", " sh
Reprint the current hunk with line IDs.
.TP
.BR again ", " a
Clear state and start a fresh pass through all remaining hunks.
.TP
.B stop
Clear all state and exit the session.
.TP
.B abort
Abort the session and undo all changes including commits and discards, restoring to the state when the session started.
.TP
.BR status ", " st " [" \-\-porcelain ]
Show session progress and current state. Use \fB--porcelain\fR for JSON output.
.SS Hunk Operations
.TP
.BR include ", " i
Stage the entire current hunk to the index and advance to the next hunk.
.TP
.BR skip ", " s
Mark the current hunk as skipped and advance to the next hunk.
.TP
.BR discard ", " d
Remove the current hunk from the working tree (reverse-apply) and advance to the next hunk.
.SS Line-Level Operations
.TP
.BR include " " \-\-line ", " il " \fILINE_IDS\fR"
Stage only the specified lines from the current hunk. Line IDs use the format
\fB1,3,5-7\fR.
.TP
.BR skip " " \-\-line ", " sl " \fILINE_IDS\fR"
Mark the specified lines as skipped.
.TP
.BR discard " " \-\-line ", " dl " \fILINE_IDS\fR"
Remove the specified lines from the working tree.
.SS File-Level Operations
.TP
.BR include " " \-\-file ", " if
Stage all remaining hunks in the current file.
.TP
.BR skip " " \-\-file ", " sf
Skip all remaining hunks in the current file.
.TP
.BR block-file ", " b " [\fIPATH\fR]"
Add a file to .gitignore and permanently exclude it from review. If no path is
provided, uses the current hunk's file.
.TP
.BR unblock-file ", " ub " \fIPATH\fR"
Remove a file from permanent exclusion.
.SS Fixup Suggestions
.TP
.BR suggest-fixup ", " x " [\fIBOUNDARY\fR] [" \-\-reset "] [" \-\-abort "] [" \-\-last "] [" \-\-line " \fILINE_IDS\fR]"
Iteratively suggest which commits the current hunk should be fixed up to,
starting with the most recent and progressing backwards. Uses \fBgit log -L\fR
to find commits that modified the hunk's lines. Each invocation shows the next
older commit (Candidate 1, 2, 3...).
.RS
.PP
Default boundary is \fB@{upstream}\fR on first call. Subsequent calls continue
with the same boundary unless changed (which auto-resets). State auto-resets
when switching hunks.
.PP
Flags:
.IP \fB\-\-reset\fR
Reset iteration and start over from the most recent commit.
.IP \fB\-\-abort\fR
Clear iteration state and exit without showing candidates.
.IP \fB\-\-last\fR
Re-show the last candidate without advancing.
.IP "\fB\-\-line\fR \fILINE_IDS\fR"
Analyze only specific line IDs (e.g., '1,3,5-7').
.RE
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-i ", " \-\-interactive
Enter interactive mode, similar to \fBgit add -p\fR but with state persistence.
.TP
.B \-\-version
Show version information and exit.
.SH INTERACTIVE MODE
When invoked with \fB-i\fR or \fB--interactive\fR, the tool enters an interactive
prompt mode where you can process hunks one-by-one without typing the full
command each time:
.PP
.nf
.RS
\fBy\fR, \fBi\fR, \fBinclude\fR - stage this hunk
\fBn\fR, \fBs\fR, \fBskip\fR    - skip this hunk for now
\fBd\fR, \fBdiscard\fR  - discard this hunk from working tree
\fBq\fR, \fBquit\fR     - quit interactive mode
\fBa\fR, \fBall\fR      - stage all remaining hunks
\fBl\fR, \fBlines\fR    - interactively select specific lines
\fBf\fR, \fBfile\fR     - stage or skip entire file
\fBb\fR, \fBblock\fR    - block current file (add to .gitignore)
\fBx\fR, \fBsuggest-fixup\fR - suggest which commit to fixup
\fB!\fR          - run a shell command
\fB?\fR          - print help
.RE
.fi
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Basic Usage
.PP
Stage changes for multiple commits:
.PP
.nf
.RS
$ git-stage-batch start
# Review first hunk
$ git-stage-batch include
# Stage it
$ git-stage-batch include
# Stage next one
$ git commit -m "First feature"
$ git-stage-batch again
# Continue with remaining hunks
.RE
.fi
.SS Line-Level Staging
.PP
Stage only specific lines from a hunk:
.PP
.nf
.RS
$ git-stage-batch start
# Hunk shows lines [#1] through [#10]
$ git-stage-batch include --line 1,3,5-7
# Stage just those lines
$ git-stage-batch skip --line 2,4
# Skip others
.RE
.fi
.SS Creating Fixup Commits
.PP
Iteratively find the right commit to fixup:
.PP
.nf
.RS
$ git-stage-batch start
# See a bug fix
$ git-stage-batch suggest-fixup origin/main
# Candidate 1: abc123 Add feature X
# ...diff...
# Run: git commit --fixup=abc123

# Not the right one? Continue iteration
$ git-stage-batch suggest-fixup
# Candidate 2: def456 Implement validation
# ...diff...
# Run: git commit --fixup=def456

# That's the one!
$ git-stage-batch include
$ git commit --fixup=def456
.RE
.fi
.PP
For hunks with changes from multiple commits:
.PP
.nf
.RS
$ git-stage-batch start
# Lines #1-3 are from one commit, #4-6 from another
$ git-stage-batch suggest-fixup --line 1-3 origin/main
# Candidate 1: abc123 ...
$ git-stage-batch include --line 1-3
$ git commit --fixup=abc123

$ git-stage-batch suggest-fixup --line 4-6
# Continues with same boundary, shows candidate for lines 4-6
# Candidate 1: def456 ...
$ git-stage-batch include --line 4-6
$ git commit --fixup=def456
.RE
.fi
.SS Interactive Mode
.PP
.nf
.RS
$ git-stage-batch -i
# Presents each hunk with a prompt
# Type 'i' to include, 's' to skip, etc.
.RE
.fi
.SH STATE DIRECTORY
State is maintained in \fB.git/git-stage-batch/\fR including:
.IP \(bu 2
Current hunk being reviewed
.IP \(bu
Blocklist of already-processed hunks
.IP \(bu
Abort state for undoing changes
.IP \(bu
Iteration counter and progress tracking
.PP
The state directory is automatically cleaned by \fBstop\fR and \fBabort\fR.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success
.TP
.B 1
Error or no hunks to process
.TP
.B 2
No pending hunks (after \fBstart\fR or in interactive mode)
.SH FILES
.TP
.B .git/git-stage-batch/
State directory for current session
.TP
.B .gitignore
Modified by \fBblock-file\fR and \fBunblock-file\fR commands
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR git (1),
.BR git-add (1),
.BR git-commit (1),
.BR git-diff (1)
.PP
Full documentation: <https://github.com/halfline/git-stage-batch>
.SH AUTHOR
Ray Strode <rstrode@redhat.com>
